Where I come from, Calcutta, mosquitoes are so ubiquitous that you become oblivious to their constant drone. The common ones belong to Anopheles, Culex, Mansonides, and the one shown here, Aedes. My garden is full of these Aedes aegypti! I've seen their babies squiggling in mugs and pots of water left stagnant in bathrooms or our backyard. This is why we always throw out stagnant water in my home. The municipal authorities guys often come and pour some film to cover stagnant lakes and ponds in the neighborhood in the summer months, and sometimes spray adulticides in our garden. This reminds me... it's April, which means that it's dengue season in India. My grand-mom sometimes kills mosquitoes using books, and so I often find splotches of dried blood and dead mosquitoes preserved between pages. I don't kill mosquitoes, because I don't kill any animals or insects. I believe that prevention is a better approach, so please don't leave stagnant water lying around. :)

"Surely Allah is not ashamed to set forth a parable even of a mosquito or any thing above that;" (Quran 2:26)

As people are invited to contemplate their own creation, the Qur'an frequently calls people to investigate nature and to see the signs of Allah therein. The whole universe, with all its living and non-living elements, consists of the signs revealing that they have been 'created'. And they exist just in order to demonstrate the power, knowledge, and art of their 'Creator'. Mankind is responsible to know these signs and appreciate the Creator of all, Allah. All living things possess these signs, yet there are some specifically mentioned animals in the Qur'an. The mosquito is one of these. This is referred to in the Qur'an in the below verse:

"Surely Allah is not ashamed to set forth any parable- (that of) a gnat or any thing above that; then as for those who believe, they know that it is the truth from their Lord, and as for those who disbelieve, they say: What is it that Allah means by this parable: He causes many to err by it and many He leads aright by it! but He does not cause to err by it (any) except the transgressors," [Al-Baqara (The Cow) 26]

When considering the life of the mosquito, we can say that it has a very extraordinary adventure. What is generally known about mosquitoes is that they absorb and feed on blood. Yet, this is not completely true. Because not all mosquitoes, but only the female ones absorb blood. And their need for blood is actually not related to feeding at all. Actually, both male and female mosquitoes feed on nectar of flowers. The only reason that females, unlike males, do absorb blood is for their eggs, which need to mature with the help of proteins contained in blood. In other words, the female mosquito absorbs blood just to ensure the survival of the new generation.

The point to be stressed here is that the verse of the Qur'an points out only the 'female' mosquito. It is only the female mosquito which has the superior capabilities that will be detailed here. So, it is surely quite expressive that female mosquitoes are particularly emphasized in the Qur'an. Besides, it is a remarkable fact to point out that at the time of the revelation of the Qur'an, the specific biology of the mosquito was knowledge unknown to mankind.

Two good ecological ways of getting rid of these little creeps (I got Dengue once, and enjoy hunting them down) is: 1.  Spray them with soapy water.  They drop like flies.  Get a spray bottle that doesn't spray in a donut hole shape or they will escape.  A bottle that shoots a stream is good; you can get them on the ceiling and far away.  2.  A hand held vaccuum cleaner  with extension.  Just move it slowly towards them and suck them in.  And use the light on your cell phone if the light is dim in your room.  Remember they like to sit on dark materials, especially your clothes.  If you live in the tropics, use mosquito netting not only on the bed, also doorways, and replace a window pane with screen material.  Good hunting!

The reason we feel itchy after being bitten by mosquito is because of their saliva.

In their saliva, there are some enzymes deactivating platelet, which means that their saliva makes our blood not to be hardened.

Our bodies, however, try to fix this unbalance. This process is conducted by our hormone, called histamine. This histamine widen our blood vessels, so that our bodies fighter; White Blood Cells could come and fight against the toxins. In this process we feel itchiness.
Adlfter the dog-fight, we feel some heat from the part where mosquito bit, because there the heat produced after the dogfight between WBCs and the toxins.

(This was what I researched and understood from the internet. If there are more intelligent scientists here, please correct and criticise me.)

I have a 55-gallon pond which contains about a hundred Gambusia (mosquito fish).  I collect rainwater in large buckets.  All spring and into summer, I net the mosquito larvae from the rainwater buckets and feed the larvae to my Gambusia. Poor little larvae. What people don't get is that it takes a while and a more than a smattering of water to attract an egg-laying female mosquito. Enough water so that the  eggs have a chance to morph into larvae and the larvae into adults. It takes longer than a few days. A few years back,  I had neighbors who came into my yard and sprinkled pesticides into my birdbaths, as they made their way up to my front door. Idiots. It was another neighbor who was hatching out mossies, not me.  I soon educated these pesticidal neighbors. Bird baths never retain water long enough to provide "habitat" for mosquito larvae---especially not if birds are bathing daily and splashing out all the water.

In Viet Nam mosquitos are farmed for their nutritious eggs.
Tires are one of the most overlooked mosquito breeding sites. They hold water whether standing up or lying down. If you have tires out of doors, empty them out and store them out of the rain, or in stacks with a lid on top.
Home ponds are another source of mosquitos. If you have one, please take very good care of it. One pond can breed millions of mosquitos. Mosquito eating fish are often eaten by birds unless the pond is screened. A tight fly screen cover will stop breeding of mosquitos.
Be sure water tanks have flyscreen on both top lid and overflow pipe. Beware pf plastic sheets or tarps filling up with water. Check your area for breeding sites and encourage neighbours to check their properties. Clean your roof gutters a couple of times a year, and do not allow too much vegetation to constantly fill the gutters. Empty and clean water storage tanks when necessary.
If you live near a watercourse, keep an eye out for stagnant pools. They can often be repaired by restoring flow through unblocking channels and so on. Small stagnant ponds can be bailed out and the water used for watering as it is also is a fertile material for dressing pasture or gardens.
Animal watering bowls and troughs also need to be kept very clean.

Pet peeve: the intro.
1) The vast majority of mosquito species, of which there are hundreds, are completely harmless. Lumping all mosquitoes into a single group and saying that it is the most deadliest animal is wrong because they do not constitute a single species.
2)The vast majority of mosquito bites are completely harmless. The number of bites required to be harmed in any significant way is in the thousands.
3) Even out of those bites that infect you with something, most of those infections aren't deadly. Of the tiny fraction of all mosquito bites are deadly, zero of them are due to the MOSQUITO being deadly. They're deadly because of non-animal organisms the mosquitoes were infected with. Mosquitoes don't kill anyone, viral and parasitic infections kill lots of people.
4) Those organisms are usually parasites on the mosquito too, the mosquito is as much a victim of them as humans are. In addition, the majority of those parasites are acquired from humans. The mosquito was infected by a human. If we are putting all of the responsibility of the infection's effects on the source of the infection, then humans would be just as good of a scapegoat then mosquitoes. (and of course, humans are deadly through other ways too- direct ways such as humans killing other humans, and indirect ways such as humans infecting other humans. Humans are therefore the deadliest animal to humans)

Как комар пьет кровь: видео
Вы думали, что комар сосет кровь через трубочку? Как бы не так: у комара не один инструмент, а целый набор — буры, насосы, шприцы и крепежные конструкции.

Ни одно другое животное на Земле не убивает столько людей, сколько комары. Конечно, не сами комары (хотя они тоже могут), а вирусы болезней, которые они переносят. Малярия, лихорадка денге, болезнь Зика — список обширен. Возбудители всех этих болезней передаются человеку, когда самка комара вводит в кожу свою иглу.

Нет, на самом деле у комара не одна, а шесть игл. На концах двух из них находятся зубья, которыми комар бурит кожу. Эти инструменты настолько тонкие, что человек почти не чувствует укус. Когда отверстие в коже проделано, комар погружает в него гибкую иглу-насос, которая поднимает вверх кровь, а другие иглы в это время служат распорками, расширяя отверстие.

Через одну из игл комар как будто шприцем вводит антикоагулянт, который не дает крови сворачиваться и облегчает ее перекачку. Именно в этот момент мы чувствуем жжение.

Цель самки — получить как можно больше крови, чтобы отложить яйца. Поэтому когда ее брюшко заполняется, она стремится слить лишнюю воду, чтобы освободить место для крови.

Комариное потомство растет в водоемах — даже небольшая открытая емкость с водой в вашем саду дает им возможность размножаться.

Areas where mosquitoes are such a problem should introduce the tactics used during the construction of the Panama Canal to wipe out the mosquito population. Since they could not proceed with construction since disease was so rampant, they looked at how they could solve the problem. One way was to eliminate pools of standing/stagnant water; areas where mosquitoes could breed and spread disease.

As mentioned in this video, mosquitoes lay their eggs on the surface of standing water and when the larvae hatch, they swim and live just below the surface. Therefore, the "sanitation" effort put forth went out to eliminate standing water where possible(which included draining swamps and ponds) and by spreading oil on the surface of any remaining pools, killing the larvae. Also, they introduced domestic water systems into the area, eliminating the need for rain collection.

It took about 2 years to prepare and enforce the effort and it ultimately ended in a success. Yellow fever and malaria were completely wiped out of the canal zone, still benefiting the people who live there today.
